Harry Potter's Literary Magic
PRINCETON — This summer, readers around the world celebrated the 20th anniversary of the first edition of J.K. Rowling's Harry Potter series — Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone (known as Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone in the United States) — at literary festivals and bookstores. They have ample reason to do so.
Sixteen years ago, on June 26, 1997, this young wizard made his first appearance, and this "boy who lived" has become a symbol of "endurance and resilience."
In the past 20 years, the Harry Potter series has expanded to include seven novels, been translated into more than 70 languages, and sold over 450 million copies.
The eight films based on the book have grossed $7 billion, while Harry Potter-themed toys and merchandise have generated another $7 billion in revenue.
For those with a literary mindset and at a certain age, it's hard to imagine a day when global audiences were not captivated by J.K. Rowling's works.
Thus, I am always amazed to recall my students' poor reaction to "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone," which I had included in the syllabus for my popular literature course at Princeton University in the fall of 1999. I have been teaching a series of courses on bestsellers since 1993.
The course studies popular works from the 17th century to the present, inviting students to ponder why and how these bestsellers attract their audiences.
At the end of each semester, I ask my students to choose a final work that represents popular tastes.
In 1999, they chose the first Harry Potter novel.
That year, the Potter fever fiercely struck the U.S. coast.
In June, the American publisher of the series rushed to push the hardcover edition of Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets, the second installment of the Harry Potter series, into bookstores.
The institution also published the third installment of the series, Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban, as well as the paperback version of Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone in September 8th.
By the end of the month, Rowling's novels had dominated the top three slots on The New York Times bestseller list, while the paperback version of Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone topped the paperback bestseller chart.
The magazine even featured this bespectacled wizard on its cover.
目光所及之处，哈利波特的形象随处可见。
我的学生迫不及待地想知道这样的狂热究竟是为什么。
天哪，他们失望透顶。
在他们看来，《哈利波特》系列不过是二流的胡言乱语，与他们童年记忆中珍藏的《纳尼亚传奇》或《指环王》等系列作品相比根本上不了台面。
尽管他们的童年刚刚过去短短几年，但他们却像许多臭名昭著的成人评论家那样指责《哈利波特》：“生编硬造”、“文笔糟糕”、“陈词滥调”、“令人厌烦”。

In their view, Harry possessed neither wonder nor wit and warmth.
The students' disgust surprised me, but in retrospect, it wasn't something to be overly alarmed about.
While adults made up a significant portion of The Harry Potter audience from the start, these students were in the wrong age bracket to objectively recognize the phenomenon.
They were past the age of accepting new children's literature, yet still too young to have their own children (I had just become a parent at the time), eagerly insisting that despite the series' current popularity, it would soon be forgotten.
Second-year students chose "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone" as their final analysis book the autumn of the following year, 2000, just like their predecessors, confidently rejecting the book.
Let's fast forward to spring 2007.
A few years after temporarily suspending the course, I taught "Bestsellers in America" again.
When the students chose their final analysis book, they selected "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone."
And I was prepared to face their criticism.
But this time, their comments were very positive.
This is a new generation of students, born between 1986 and 1989, who initially read J.K. Rowling's works not as university students but as teenagers just entering adolescence. This means they grew up alongside Harry, Ron, and Hermione.
It happened again in autumn 2010.
To these students, "We grew up with Harry Potter" has become a motto, not a label.
Will Harry ever disappear from our memories?
As long as we are alive, it is impossible.
I have taught bestseller courses twice since 2010, and on both occasions, the students chose non-Harry Potter novels for their final reviews.
Are they tired of Potter?
Based on the feedback I received when teaching Rowling's works in another course called "Children's Literature," this seems unlikely.
Now, I have chosen to include a Harry Potter novel in my syllabus, but I did not choose "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone," instead opting for "Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban" – which is my favorite book in the seven-book series and marks the transition from children's literature to young adult fiction, offering a complex portrayal of loyalty, betrayal, anger, and compassion.
The book is also one of my students' favorites.
But how long will the popularity of the Harry Potter series last?
Every time I teach children's literature, I first conduct a poll: "Which books on the list did you read when you were a child?"
In 2010, 86% of people had read Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban.
In 2012, that number rose to 94%.
But in the years that followed, the percentage continued to decline — — 87% in 2014, dropping to 81% in 2016.
These are not scientific data, I know.
But I am curious: Will the percentage drop below 80% next spring when I teach "Children's Literature" again, when more students have read Harry Potter?
Will it turn out that the students from 1999 to 2000 were right, that Harry Potter's status is continuously declining and will never become a classic work?
Or will there be a point of balance where the percentage stabilizes and no longer declines?
Perhaps Harry's 40th anniversary will tell us the answer.
Until then, I am very happy to continue inviting him into my class.
